matches=readRDS("/users/tarkantemizoz/desktop/some_league_id_matches.rds")

##PART A
##operations on matches_scores data
#removing the unnecessary columns for this task, namely leagueId, home and away teams and type
matches_scores=matches[,c("leagueId","home","away","type"):=NULL]
#transforming date data from unix time
matches_scores=matches_scores[,date:=anytime(date)]
#getting match scores into two different columns
matches_scores=matches_scores[,c("H","A"):=tstrsplit(score,':')]
matches_scores=matches_scores[,score:=NULL]
#checking structure of matches_scores data to see the of transformations
str(matches_scores)
## Classes 'data.table' and 'data.frame':   3119 obs. of  4 variables:
##  $ matchId: chr  "KjF6FiA6" "ILVbJgQm" "SGIEDVvJ" "YwL5xFHJ" ...
##  $ date   : POSIXct, format: "2010-08-14 16:45:00" "2010-08-14 19:00:00" ...
##  $ H      : chr  "0" "3" "2" "0" ...
##  $ A      : chr  "0" "0" "1" "0" ...
##  - attr(*, ".internal.selfref")=<externalptr>
#transforming the structure of "H" and "A" into numeric from character
matches_scores$H=as.numeric(matches_scores$H)
matches_scores$A=as.numeric(matches_scores$A)
#determing whether a match results over or under
matches_scores=matches_scores[H+A<2.5,over_under:=0]
matches_scores=matches_scores[H+A>2.5,over_under:=1]
matches_scores=matches_scores[,c("H","A"):=NULL]
#removing all NA's from data
matches_scores=matches_scores[complete.cases(matches_scores)]
#getting the year information
matches_scores=matches_scores[,date:=year(date)]

##operations on odds data
#filtering over under bets for 2.5 goals
odds_over_under=odds[betType=='ou' & totalhandicap=='2.5']
#removing the unnecessary columns for this task, namely totalhandicap and betType
odds_over_under[,totalhandicap:=NULL]
odds_over_under[,betType:=NULL]
#ordering odds data to determine initial and final odds given
odds_over_under=odds_over_under[order(matchId, oddtype,bookmaker,date)]
#initial odds data, we can omit the date column as we don't need it anymore
odds_over_under_initial=odds_over_under[,list(initial_odd=odd[1]),by=list(matchId,oddtype,bookmaker)]
#final odds data, we can omit the date column as we don't need it anymore
odds_over_under_final=odds_over_under[,list(final_odd=odd[.N]),by=list(matchId,oddtype,bookmaker)]
##removing all NA's from data
odds_over_under_initial=odds_over_under_initial[complete.cases(odds_over_under_initial)]
odds_over_under_final=odds_over_under_final[complete.cases(odds_over_under_final)]

##five bet companies to analyze with their initial and final odds

#PINNACLE
#probability calculations for both initial and final odds
matches_scores_nodate=matches_scores[,date:=NULL]
pinnacle_over_under_final=odds_over_under_final[bookmaker=='Pinnacle']
pinnacle_over_under_final_wide=dcast(pinnacle_over_under_final,matchId~oddtype,value.var='final_odd')
pinnacle_over_under_final=merge(matches_scores_nodate,pinnacle_over_under_final_wide,by='matchId')
pinnacle_over_under_final=pinnacle_over_under_final[,finprobOver:=1/over]
pinnacle_over_under_final=pinnacle_over_under_final[,finprobUnder:=1/under]
pinnacle_over_under_final=pinnacle_over_under_final[,fintotalProb:=finprobOver+finprobUnder]
pinnacle_over_under_final=pinnacle_over_under_final[,finprobOver:=finprobOver/(fintotalProb)]
pinnacle_over_under_final=pinnacle_over_under_final[,finprobUnder:=finprobUnder/(fintotalProb)]
pinnacle_over_under_final=pinnacle_over_under_final[,fintotalProb:=NULL]
cutpoints=c(0,seq(0.41,0.63,0.01),1)
pinnacle_over_under_final=pinnacle_over_under_final[,odd_cut_over:=cut(finprobOver,cutpoints)]
pinnacle_table_final=pinnacle_over_under_final[,list(empirical_over=mean(over_under),probabilistic_over=mean(finprobOver),.N),by=list(odd_cut_over)]
pinnacle_over_under_initial=odds_over_under_initial[bookmaker=='Pinnacle']
pinnacle_over_under_initial_wide=dcast(pinnacle_over_under_initial,matchId~oddtype,value.var='initial_odd')
pinnacle_over_under_initial=merge(matches_scores_nodate,pinnacle_over_under_initial_wide,by='matchId')
pinnacle_over_under_initial=pinnacle_over_under_initial[,inprobOver:=1/over]
pinnacle_over_under_initial=pinnacle_over_under_initial[,inprobUnder:=1/under]
pinnacle_over_under_initial=pinnacle_over_under_initial[,intotalProb:=inprobOver+inprobUnder]
pinnacle_over_under_initial=pinnacle_over_under_initial[,inprobOver:=inprobOver/(intotalProb)]
pinnacle_over_under_initial=pinnacle_over_under_initial[,inprobUnder:=inprobUnder/(intotalProb)]
pinnacle_over_under_initial=pinnacle_over_under_initial[,intotalProb:=NULL]
cutpoints=c(0,seq(0.41,0.63,0.01),1)
pinnacle_over_under_initial=pinnacle_over_under_initial[,odd_cut_over:=cut(inprobOver,cutpoints)]
pinnacle_table_initial=pinnacle_over_under_initial[,list(empirical_over=mean(over_under),probabilistic_over=mean(inprobOver),.N),by=list(odd_cut_over)]
#plotting probability averages in a bin versus the fraction of games finished over
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(pinnacle_table_final[,list(empirical_over,probabilistic_over)],cex=0.3,xlab="Fraction of games finished over",ylab="Probability Average",main="Final Odds")
abline(0,1,col='red')
lines(lowess(pinnacle_table_final$empirical_over,pinnacle_table_final$probabilistic_over), col="blue", lwd=1)
plot(pinnacle_table_initial[,list(empirical_over,probabilistic_over)],cex=0.3,xlab="Fraction of games finished over",ylab="Probability Average",main="Initial Odds")
abline(0,1,col='red')
lines(lowess(pinnacle_table_initial$empirical_over,pinnacle_table_initial$probabilistic_over), col="blue", lwd=1)

#Pinnacle may seem successful at setting their odds since the trend line between fraction of the games finished over and probability average almost follow the x=y line, but being on the right side of it favours betters for high probability games; in addition, their initial odds show a slightly better result.
#We may make a profit by playing games having probability average more than 0.45.

#The red points are the probabilities from the bookmakers representing the probability of draw versus the probablity of home win minus away win. The black line is the fitted line to those red points. In addition, the blue dots, namely the binned outcomes, are the actual occurrences of those games. For this analysis, the matches are ordered according to their probability of home win minus probability of away win and then they form bins of 40 games. we calculated how many games resulted draw for each bin and find the corresponding probability. The blue points represent these probabilities.
#For a successful bookmaker which correctly guess the outcome probabilities, we expect the odds probabilities and binned outcomes show a similar distribution; however, as seen in the graphs, the distribution looks like the same but the blue points are more spread, so we can make money for this difference.
#For the binned outcomes that are above the trend line, the bookmaker "Pinnacle" tend to underrate the probability of draw giving the high odds. These games are mostly accumulated between (-0.01,0.02) for P(HOME)-P(AWAY). If we bet for the games between these thresholds, it can be assumed that we can make profit.
#Our analysis also show that the red points, the probabilities from the bookmakers, have a higher peak points and the trend line is a little bit above than the one for initial odds.
#As a result, Pinnacle succesfuly estimates the move that whether they should increase or decrease an odd; however, their moves are so small(see the graph, it is very small) that we can still gain and deduce that for example if Pinnacle decrease an odd, placing a bet on this odd may be smart move. 

#Another method to test odd changes is performed by how the fraction of games changes as implied probability increases or decreases for each of three type bets: home win, away win or draw
#bin sizes for probability changes are set so that each bin includes enough number of games to analyse.
pinnacle_1X2=pinnacle_1X2[,diffprob1:=finprob1-inprob1]
cutpoints=c(min(pinnacle_1X2$diffprob1)-0.01,seq(-0.05,0.05,0.005),max(pinnacle_1X2$diffprob1)+0.01)
pinnacle_1X2=pinnacle_1X2[,odd_cut:=cut(diffprob1,cutpoints)]
pinnacle_1X2_table=pinnacle_1X2[,list(empirical_1=count(score==1)[2,2],.N),by=list(odd_cut)]
pinnacle_1X2_table$empirical_1=pinnacle_1X2_table$empirical_1/pinnacle_1X2_table$N
pinnacle_1X2_table=pinnacle_1X2_table[order(odd_cut)]
plot(pinnacle_1X2_table$odd_cut,pinnacle_1X2_table$empirical_1,ylab="Fraction of games ended home win",xlab="Probability change")
lines(lowess(pinnacle_1X2_table$odd_cut,pinnacle_1X2_table$empirical_1), col="black", lwd=1)

#we see that as probability change increases in the favor of home team side, the fraction of games ended as home team win also increases. A succesful move for Pinnacle.

pinnacle_1X2=pinnacle_1X2[,diffprob2:=finprob2-inprob2]
cutpoints=c(min(pinnacle_1X2$diffprob2)-0.01,seq(-0.05,0.05,0.005),max(pinnacle_1X2$diffprob2)+0.01)
pinnacle_1X2=pinnacle_1X2[,odd_cut:=cut(diffprob2,cutpoints)]
pinnacle_1X2_table=pinnacle_1X2[,list(empirical_2=count(score==2)[2,2],.N),by=list(odd_cut)]
pinnacle_1X2_table$empirical_2=pinnacle_1X2_table$empirical_2/pinnacle_1X2_table$N
pinnacle_1X2_table=pinnacle_1X2_table[order(odd_cut)]

lines(lowess(pinnacle_1X2_table$odd_cut,pinnacle_1X2_table$empirical_2), col="black", lwd=1)

#we see that as probability change increases in the favor of away team side, the fraction of games ended as away team win first decreases then increases. A doubtful move for Pinnacle.

pinnacle_1X2=pinnacle_1X2[,diffprob0:=finprob0-inprob0]

pinnacle_1X2=pinnacle_1X2[,odd_cut:=cut(diffprob0,cutpoints)]

pinnacle_1X2_table=pinnacle_1X2_table[order(odd_cut)]

lines(lowess(pinnacle_1X2_table$odd_cut,pinnacle_1X2_table$empirical_0), col="black", lwd=1)

#we see that as positive probability changes for draw, the fraction of games ended as draw shows a steady upward move. For negative probability changes the fraction of games ended draw also decreases. A successful move for Pinnacle. We should not place bet on match score draw if its odds increases. 

#Overall, Pinnacle is a successful bookmaker in terms of adjusting their odds.

#As a last method to test our hypothesis we can plot final odds against initial odds for home win, away win and draw, respectively, and place the fraction of games ended home win, away win or draw on the same plot. This way we can also see how the bookmaker performs.
